Note that you could also use the `&lt;input&gt;` tag directly, which would allow you to set the image as a background.

Also note `top` and `left` will only work on an element that is positioned (one that has an ancestor with `position` set), and that high `px` units won&#39;t render well on small devices.

So, you could always give this slightly different approach a go! 

See: [JSFiddle][1]

It requires a **lot less** wrapped classes &amp; doesn&#39;t use the `Imgur` image you&#39;ve listed, instead uses an `icon set` called Font Awesome. You can learn about Font Awesome [here][2].

This is my example, along with how to reference the `icon set`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .search_box {
       border-radius: 15px;
       background-color: #edf3f9;
       opacity: 0.8;
       border: none;
       height: 20px;
       line-height: 20px;
       color: black;
       text-indent: 40px;
       width: 200px;
       position: relative;
    }

    .search_box::placeholder{   
       opacity: 0.9;
       color: black;
    }

    .search_box::-webkit-input-placeholder{   
       opacity: 0.9;
       color: black;
    }

    .search_box:-ms-input-placeholder{
       opacity: 0.9;
       color: black;
    }

    #search_icon {
      position: relative;
      z-index: 99;
      left: 30px;
       opacity: 0.8;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot; href=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/font-awesome/4.7.0/css/font-awesome.min.css&quot;&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;
     &lt;i class=&quot;fa fa-search&quot; id=&quot;search_icon&quot;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
     &lt;input type=&quot;text&quot; class=&quot;search_box&quot; placeholder=&quot;Search...&quot;/&gt; 
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Essentially, all my code does is:

 1. List `Font Awesome`&#39;s icon set as an external reference, you can see how to do this [here][3]
 2. Have a tag containing the icon, the icon is referenced by class, you can see all `Font Awesome` icons [here][4]
 3. Create an `input` tag to be your `textbox`
 4. Style this accordingly with `border-radius` and `opacity`
 5. Ensure the `&lt;i&gt;` tag has a `z-index` higher than the `textbox` such that it is on top
 6. Ensure the `textbox` and `&lt;i&gt;` tag have `position:relative` such that they are not impacted if you have elements above them
 7. Do some basic alignment so that the search icon sits in the correct position in the searchbox 

Goodluck with it! Even if you don&#39;t implement this, hopefully it&#39;s informative :)


