You just use two seperate numbers and put them together to where you want them to show.

You have a method `IncrementCurrentNumber` that just increases the first number:

    int currentNumber = 0;
    void IncrementCurrentNumber()
    {
      currentNumber++;
    }

And you have another method that increases the year and resets the current number:

int year = 2019;

    void IncrementYear()
    {
      year++;
      currentNumber = 0;
    }

Then you get the actual serial number by joining both:

    string GetNextSerialNumber()
    {
      IncrementCurrentNumber();
      return currentNumber+&quot;/&quot;+year;
    }

And whenever you want to increment year, e.g. with a button, you call the `IncrementYear()` method.

Edit: And the comments are of course right, if you want it to automatically use the current year, you&#39;ll have to use DateTime.Now.Year to get that and also have the program remember the last serial number, so you can check whether or not you have to reset the `currentNumber`.

One way to do this is to simply store a map of the last used id along with the current year, which should be done in a database but could also be done in a dictionary (which is easier to show in a code sample):

    private static readonly Dictionary&lt;int, int&gt; YearIdMap = new Dictionary&lt;int, int&gt;();

    public static string GetNextId()
    {
        // Get the current year
        int year = DateTime.Today.Year;

        // Something to store the next id value in
        int nextId;

        // Sets nextId to the current id for this year, or 0 if there isn&#39;t one yet
        YearIdMap.TryGetValue(year, out nextId); 

        // Increment our number
        nextId++;

        // Save the new value along with this year
        YearIdMap[year] = nextId;

        // Return the value to the caller in the format: id/year
        return $&quot;{nextId}/{year}&quot;;
    }

